{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Fx1j27uAgK3vo4WoJphGR5","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 25 → 26 Improvement Plan\n     2→\n     3→## Title\n     4→\n     5→Fix OCR preamble artifact leaking into compound title assembly\n     6→\n     7→## Status\n     8→\n     9→Draft\n    10→\n    11→## Authors\n    12→\n    13→Claude — 2026-03-17\n    14→\n    15→## Overview\n    16→\n    17→Iteration 25 has 1 real-file failure and 0 generated-file failures. The single failure\n    18→is a compound title where an OCR artifact from a preceding page (`DAT FLATBREADS`) is\n    19→selected instead of the correct second recipe title (`FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS`).\n    20→\n    21→The fix introduces **vocabulary corroboration** — a lightweight check that validates\n    22→ALL_CAPS title candidates against the rest of the document before including them in\n    23→multi-title output. This targets the specific failure mode (orphaned OCR artifacts\n    24→masquerading as titles) without disrupting the existing scoring pipeline.\n    25→\n    26→## Background / Problem Statement\n    27→\n    28→### The failure\n    29→\n    30→- **Expected:** `FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS`\n    31→- **Extracted:** `DAT FLATBREADS + FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS`\n    32→\n    33→The input file contains OCR overflow from a preceding recipe on lines 1–5. Line 4 reads\n    34→`DAT FLATBREADS` — a truncated/corrupted remnant of the previous page's title (likely\n    35→\"OAT FLATBREADS\" or similar). Because it is ALL_CAPS and 2 words, it passes every hard\n    36→filter and looks structurally identical to a real recipe title.\n    37→\n    38→The multi-title logic finds 3 ALL_CAPS candidates (`DAT FLATBREADS`, `FINNISH MILK\n    39→FLATBREADS`, `FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS`), keeps all 3 (non-first candidates aren't\n    40→sub-headers), caps at 3, and joins them. The extracted result is the first two.\n    41→\n    42→Wait — the extracted output is only 2 titles, not 3. This means either:\n    43→(a) `FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS` on line 29 was filtered or failed to enter the candidate\n    44→pool (the 25-candidate cap may exclude it), or\n    45→(b) dedup or sub-header logic removed it.\n    46→\n    47→Either way, the root cause is the same: `DAT FLATBREADS` shouldn't be in the pool at all.\n    48→\n    49→### Why existing defenses don't catch it\n    50→\n    51→| Defense | Why it fails |\n    52→|---------|-------------|\n    53→| `findBurstEnd` | Skips garbled lines, but `DAT FLATBREADS` is clean ALL_CAPS — burst detection stops before it |\n    54→| `isLikelyGarbled` | \"DAT\" has vowels, no mixed scripts, no pipes — passes |\n    55→| `passesHardFilters` | 2 words, all-caps, no ingredients/metadata — passes |\n    56→| Embedding scoring | \"DAT FLATBREADS\" embeds close to \"recipe name, dish title\" — decent rawScore |\n    57→| Structural heading | ALL_CAPS with ≥2 words, ≥4 alpha letters each — qualifies |\n    58→\n    59→The extractor has no mechanism to ask: \"Does this candidate's vocabulary appear elsewhere\n    60→in the document?\" For real titles, the answer is almost always yes (the recipe body\n    61→references the dish name, ingredients, or key terms). For orphaned OCR artifacts, the\n    62→answer is typically no.\n    63→\n    64→### What works well (do not change)\n    65→\n    66→- The overall pipeline: candidate generation → hard filters → embedding scoring → multi-title assembly\n    67→- Dictionary-guided OCR repair (iteration 24) — no regressions\n    68→- Compound title dedup protection (iteration 24) — working correctly\n    69→- Bilingual detection and fallback hierarchy — stable\n    70→- Generated file accuracy: 0 failures — the synthetic test suite is fully passing\n    71→\n    72→## Goals\n    73→\n    74→- Fix the 1 real-file failure (FINNISH MILK/POTATO FLATBREADS)\n    75→- Do not regress any currently-passing real or generated files\n    76→- Keep the fix minimal and targeted — the system is 90.9% accurate with 0 generated failures\n    77→\n    78→## Non-Goals\n    79→\n    80→- Replacing the embedding model or scoring architecture\n    81→- Reworking the multi-title assembly logic broadly\n    82→- Fixing hypothetical future failure modes not evidenced by current test data\n    83→- Adding new generated test files\n    84→\n    85→---\n    86→\n    87→## Detailed Design\n    88→\n    89→### Root cause analysis\n    90→\n    91→Looking at the actual input file:\n    92→\n    93→```\n    94→Line 1:  \"2 (/½ cup plus ı tablespoon a sland mixer fried with v for s minutes...\"  ← garbled overflow\n    95→Line 2:  \"nto a loured work counter, t es and shape into ball a a\"                   ← garbled overflow\n    96→Line 3:  \"3 pan over a medium beat y i both sides...\"                                ← garbled overflow\n    97→Line 4:  \"DAT FLATBREADS\"                                                            ← OCR artifact\n    98→Line 5:  \"le Finnish region of Savo 1a bread, it's more like a...\"                   ← body of previous recipe\n    99→...\n   100→Line 16: \"FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS\"                                                   ← correct title #1\n   101→...\n   102→Line 29: \"FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS\"                                                 ← correct title #2\n   103→```\n   104→\n   105→Lines 1–3 are clearly garbled sentence fragments (lowercase start, cut-off words). Line 4\n   106→is the tail-end of the previous recipe's title, corrupted by OCR. Lines 5+ are the body\n   107→of that previous recipe. The actual recipes in this file start at line 16.\n   108→\n   109→`findBurstEnd` skips lines 1–3 (garbled, short) but stops at line 4 because `DAT\n   110→FLATBREADS` is ALL_CAPS and not garbled. The prose-preamble check (3+ consecutive body\n   111→text lines) doesn't fire because line 4 breaks the sequence.\n   112→\n   113→### Proposed fix: Vocabulary corroboration for multi-title candidates\n   114→\n   115→Add a **corroboration score** to each ALL_CAPS candidate when the multi-title path\n   116→(≥2 ALL_CAPS survivors) is active. The score measures how many of the candidate's\n   117→content words appear elsewhere in the document body.\n   118→\n   119→#### Algorithm\n   120→\n   121→```\n   122→function corroborationScore(candidate, allLines):\n   123→  contentWords = candidate.text\n   124→    .split(/\\s+/)\n   125→    .filter(w => w.length >= 4)       // skip \"THE\", \"WITH\", \"AND\", etc.\n   126→    .map(w => w.toUpperCase())\n   127→\n   128→  if contentWords.length === 0:\n   129→    return 1.0                          // single short word — can't check, pass through\n   130→\n   131→  corroboratedCount = 0\n   132→  for word in contentWords:\n   133→    // Check if word appears in any other line (not the candidate's own line)\n   134→    for line in allLines:\n   135→      if line.position === candidate.position: continue\n   136→      if line.text.toUpperCase().includes(word):\n   137→        corroboratedCount++\n   138→        break\n   139→\n   140→  return corroboratedCount / contentWords.length\n   141→```\n   142→\n   143→**Integration point:** In the multi-title assembly block (around line 1254), after\n   144→identifying ≥2 ALL_CAPS survivors but before the sub-header check, filter out candidates\n   145→with corroboration score below a threshold (e.g., 0.5 — meaning fewer than half of the\n   146→candidate's content words appear elsewhere in the document).\n   147→\n   148→#### Why this works for the failure case\n   149→\n   150→| Candidate | Content words | Corroborated? | Score |\n   151→|-----------|--------------|---------------|-------|\n   152→| `DAT FLATBREADS` | DAT, FLATBREADS | DAT: **NO** (appears nowhere else), FLATBREADS: YES (lines 16, 29, etc.) | 0.5 |\n   153→| `FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS` | FINNISH, MILK, FLATBREADS | FINNISH: YES (lines 29, 5, etc.), MILK: YES (line 21), FLATBREADS: YES | 1.0 |\n   154→| `FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS` | FINNISH, POTATO, FLATBREADS | FINNISH: YES, POTATO: YES (line 31, 37), FLATBREADS: YES | 1.0 |\n   155→\n   156→With a threshold of 0.5 (strict >, not ≥), `DAT FLATBREADS` at exactly 0.5 would be\n   157→removed. With a threshold of `< 0.5` (keep if ≥ 0.5), it would survive.\n   158→\n   159→A safer threshold: require that **all content words of length ≥ 4** are corroborated\n   160→(score = 1.0), OR that the candidate has at least 3 content words with ≥ 2/3 corroborated.\n   161→For 2-word candidates like `DAT FLATBREADS`, this means both words must appear elsewhere.\n   162→\n   163→**Recommended rule:** For candidates with ≤ 3 content words, require 100% corroboration.\n   164→For candidates with > 3 content words, require ≥ 67% corroboration. This is strict for\n   165→short candidates (where a single uncorroborated word is suspicious) and relaxed for long\n   166→ones (where one unusual word in a longer title is acceptable).\n   167→\n   168→```typescript\n   169→const threshold = contentWords.length <= 3 ? 1.0 : 0.67;\n   170→if (corroborationScore < threshold) {\n   171→  // Remove candidate from multi-title assembly\n   172→}\n   173→```\n   174→\n   175→For `DAT FLATBREADS`: 2 content words, threshold = 1.0, score = 0.5 → **removed**.\n   176→\n   177→#### Why this is safe for other cases\n   178→\n   179→- **Single-title pages** (most recipes): Corroboration is only checked in the multi-title\n   180→  path (≥2 ALL_CAPS survivors). Single-title pages are unaffected.\n   181→\n   182→- **Legitimate compound titles** (e.g., `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE`):\n   183→  These are single candidates with compound separators, not multi-title assembly. Unaffected.\n   184→\n   185→- **Multi-recipe pages** where both titles are real: Both titles' content words will appear\n   186→  in their respective recipe bodies (ingredients, descriptions). They corroborate easily.\n   187→\n   188→- **Very short titles** (1 content word, e.g., a hypothetical `GOLONKA`): The\n   189→  `contentWords.length === 0` guard returns 1.0 for candidates with no words ≥ 4 letters.\n   190→  A single 4+ letter word would need corroboration, which is correct — if the word\n   191→  doesn't appear anywhere in the document, it's suspicious.\n   192→\n   193→### Secondary fix: Improve preamble detection for garbled-then-clean sequences\n   194→\n   195→The `findBurstEnd` function currently stops at the first non-garbled line. But when\n   196→lines 1–3 are garbled fragments and line 4 is a short ALL_CAPS string, line 4 is very\n   197→likely part of the same overflow block.\n   198→\n   199→**Proposed heuristic:** After `findBurstEnd` skips garbled lines, if the next line is\n   200→ALL_CAPS and ≤ 3 words, AND the line after that starts with lowercase (body text), treat\n   201→the ALL_CAPS line as the tail of the preamble and skip it too.\n   202→\n   203→```typescript\n   204→// In findBurstEnd, after the garbled-skip loop:\n   205→if (i > 0 && i < lines.length) {\n   206→  const next = lines[i].text;\n   207→  // If burst ended at a short ALL_CAPS fragment followed by body text,\n   208→  // it's likely the truncated title of the previous page's recipe.\n   209→  if (isAllCaps(next) && wordCount(next) <= 3 && i + 1 < lines.length) {\n   210→    const afterNext = lines[i + 1].text;\n   211→    if (/^[a-ząćęłńóśźż]/.test(afterNext) && wordCount(afterNext) >= 4) {\n   212→      i++;  // Skip the ALL_CAPS fragment too\n   213→      // Also skip the body text that follows (same prose-preamble logic)\n   214→      // ...\n   215→    }\n   216→  }\n   217→}\n   218→```\n   219→\n   220→This is a **complementary** fix. It prevents `DAT FLATBREADS` from entering the candidate\n   221→pool at all, which is cleaner than relying solely on corroboration to remove it later.\n   222→However, corroboration is the more general defense (handles cases where the preamble\n   223→detection doesn't fire).\n   224→\n   225→**Risk:** Could skip a legitimate short ALL_CAPS title at the start of a file if preceded\n   226→by garbled text. Mitigation: Only fires when `i > 0` (garbled lines were actually\n   227→skipped) AND the next line is body text (lowercase start, ≥ 4 words). A real title would\n   228→typically be followed by a subtitle or description, not body text.\n   229→\n   230→### Implementation changes\n   231→\n   232→#### File: `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`\n   233→\n   234→| Change | Location | Description |\n   235→|--------|----------|-------------|\n   236→| Add `corroborationScore()` function | New function, near scoring helpers | Compute vocabulary overlap between candidate and rest of document |\n   237→| Apply corroboration filter in multi-title path | ~line 1254, inside `allCapsSelected.length >= 2` branch | Remove ALL_CAPS candidates below corroboration threshold before sub-header check |\n   238→| Improve `findBurstEnd` for garbled-then-clean sequences | ~line 378, after garbled-skip loop | Skip short ALL_CAPS fragment after garbled burst when followed by body text |\n   239→\n   240→No new files. No changes to `food-dictionary.ts`, `embeddings.ts`, or test files.\n   241→\n   242→---\n   243→\n   244→## Testing Strategy\n   245→\n   246→### Verifying the fix\n   247→\n   248→1. **Primary:** Run the title-loop evaluation harness (`tools/title-loop/title-loop.py`)\n   249→   and confirm:\n   250→   - `FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS` now passes\n   251→   - No regressions in real or generated files\n   252→\n   253→2. **Unit test cases to add** (in `lib/text-classifier/__tests__/title-extractor.test.ts`):\n   254→\n   255→   - **Corroboration rejects orphaned artifact:** Input with garbled preamble + orphaned\n   256→     ALL_CAPS + 2 real recipe titles → only real titles returned\n   257→   - **Corroboration keeps legitimate multi-recipe:** Input with 2 ALL_CAPS titles that\n   258→     both have body text referencing their words → both kept\n   259→\n   260→3. **Edge case tests:**\n   261→   - Short ALL_CAPS title (2 words) where one word is common (\"CHICKEN SOUP\") and appears\n   262→     in body → kept (both words corroborated)\n   263→   - ALL_CAPS title with an unusual/unique word that doesn't appear in body but is\n   264→     clearly the title → still works because it's the only candidate (single-title path,\n   265→     corroboration not applied)\n   266→\n   267→### What not to test\n   268→\n   269→- Generated file generation — 0 failures, don't add new synthetic cases for this pattern\n   270→- Embedding model behavior — not changed\n   271→- OCR repair — not changed\n   272→\n   273→---\n   274→\n   275→## Performance Considerations\n   276→\n   277→The corroboration check iterates over candidate content words × document lines. With\n   278→typical values (2–4 content words, 30–50 lines), this is ~100–200 string operations.\n   279→Negligible compared to the embedding computation (which dominates the 10-second budget).\n   280→\n   281→The `findBurstEnd` improvement adds a constant-time check. No performance impact.\n   282→\n   283→---\n   284→\n   285→## Security Considerations\n   286→\n   287→None. All changes are in local text processing with no I/O or user-facing API changes.\n   288→\n   289→---\n   290→\n   291→## Implementation Phases\n   292→\n   293→### Phase 1: Core fix (single change set)\n   294→\n   295→1. Add `corroborationScore()` helper function\n   296→2. Integrate corroboration filter into multi-title assembly (≥2 ALL_CAPS branch)\n   297→3. Improve `findBurstEnd` for garbled-then-clean sequences\n   298→4. Run evaluation harness, confirm fix + no regressions\n   299→\n   300→This is a single-phase change. The fix is small and targeted.\n   301→\n   302→---\n   303→\n   304→## Open Questions\n   305→\n   306→1. **Corroboration threshold for 2-word candidates:** Should we require 100% (both words\n   307→   corroborated) or allow 50% (at least one word)? The 100% rule is safer for the known\n   308→   failure case but could be too strict for hypothetical titles with one unusual word.\n   309→   **Recommendation:** Start with 100% for ≤ 3 content words. If a regression appears,\n   310→   relax to 50%.\n   311→\n   312→2. **Should corroboration apply to single-title path too?** Currently proposed only for\n   313→   multi-title (≥2 ALL_CAPS). Applying it to single-title would add a safety net but\n   314→   risks rejecting legitimate titles with unique words. **Recommendation:** No — the\n   315→   single-title fallback hierarchy already handles this well enough.\n   316→\n   317→3. **Should `findBurstEnd` improvement be included?** It's a belt-and-suspenders approach.\n   318→   The corroboration check alone would fix the failure. The preamble detection improvement\n   319→   prevents the artifact from entering the candidate pool at all, which is cleaner.\n   320→   **Recommendation:** Include both. They address different layers of the pipeline and\n   321→   neither is risky on its own.\n   322→\n   323→---\n   324→\n   325→## References\n   326→\n   327→- Iteration 25 feedback: `tools/title-loop/docs/25-2331e30/feedback.md`\n   328→- Iteration 24 improvement plan: `tools/title-loop/docs/24-b15aa30/improvement-plan.md`\n   329→- Failing test input: `tools/title-loop/input/FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS.real.txt`\n   330→- Multi-title assembly logic: `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1245-1314`\n   331→- `findBurstEnd`: `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:355-410`\n   332→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a061f1f0-ad7a-459c-9eae-0adb758ccdd2","uuid":"79d1f5ee-29ac-4ef7-b9fe-6dc505886052","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/25-2331e30/improvement-plan.md","content":"# Iteration 25 → 26 Improvement Plan\n\n## Title\n\nFix OCR preamble artifact leaking into compound title assembly\n\n## Status\n\nDraft\n\n## Authors\n\nClaude — 2026-03-17\n\n## Overview\n\nIteration 25 has 1 real-file failure and 0 generated-file failures. The single failure\nis a compound title where an OCR artifact from a preceding page (`DAT FLATBREADS`) is\nselected instead of the correct second recipe title (`FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS`).\n\nThe fix introduces **vocabulary corroboration** — a lightweight check that validates\nALL_CAPS title candidates against the rest of the document before including them in\nmulti-title output. This targets the specific failure mode (orphaned OCR artifacts\nmasquerading as titles) without disrupting the existing scoring pipeline.\n\n## Background / Problem Statement\n\n### The failure\n\n- **Expected:** `FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS`\n- **Extracted:** `DAT FLATBREADS + FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS`\n\nThe input file contains OCR overflow from a preceding recipe on lines 1–5. Line 4 reads\n`DAT FLATBREADS` — a truncated/corrupted remnant of the previous page's title (likely\n\"OAT FLATBREADS\" or similar). Because it is ALL_CAPS and 2 words, it passes every hard\nfilter and looks structurally identical to a real recipe title.\n\nThe multi-title logic finds 3 ALL_CAPS candidates (`DAT FLATBREADS`, `FINNISH MILK\nFLATBREADS`, `FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS`), keeps all 3 (non-first candidates aren't\nsub-headers), caps at 3, and joins them. The extracted result is the first two.\n\nWait — the extracted output is only 2 titles, not 3. This means either:\n(a) `FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS` on line 29 was filtered or failed to enter the candidate\npool (the 25-candidate cap may exclude it), or\n(b) dedup or sub-header logic removed it.\n\nEither way, the root cause is the same: `DAT FLATBREADS` shouldn't be in the pool at all.\n\n### Why existing defenses don't catch it\n\n| Defense | Why it fails |\n|---------|-------------|\n| `findBurstEnd` | Skips garbled lines, but `DAT FLATBREADS` is clean ALL_CAPS — burst detection stops before it |\n| `isLikelyGarbled` | \"DAT\" has vowels, no mixed scripts, no pipes — passes |\n| `passesHardFilters` | 2 words, all-caps, no ingredients/metadata — passes |\n| Embedding scoring | \"DAT FLATBREADS\" embeds close to \"recipe name, dish title\" — decent rawScore |\n| Structural heading | ALL_CAPS with ≥2 words, ≥4 alpha letters each — qualifies |\n\nThe extractor has no mechanism to ask: \"Does this candidate's vocabulary appear elsewhere\nin the document?\" For real titles, the answer is almost always yes (the recipe body\nreferences the dish name, ingredients, or key terms). For orphaned OCR artifacts, the\nanswer is typically no.\n\n### What works well (do not change)\n\n- The overall pipeline: candidate generation → hard filters → embedding scoring → multi-title assembly\n- Dictionary-guided OCR repair (iteration 24) — no regressions\n- Compound title dedup protection (iteration 24) — working correctly\n- Bilingual detection and fallback hierarchy — stable\n- Generated file accuracy: 0 failures — the synthetic test suite is fully passing\n\n## Goals\n\n- Fix the 1 real-file failure (FINNISH MILK/POTATO FLATBREADS)\n- Do not regress any currently-passing real or generated files\n- Keep the fix minimal and targeted — the system is 90.9% accurate with 0 generated failures\n\n## Non-Goals\n\n- Replacing the embedding model or scoring architecture\n- Reworking the multi-title assembly logic broadly\n- Fixing hypothetical future failure modes not evidenced by current test data\n- Adding new generated test files\n\n---\n\n## Detailed Design\n\n### Root cause analysis\n\nLooking at the actual input file:\n\n```\nLine 1:  \"2 (/½ cup plus ı tablespoon a sland mixer fried with v for s minutes...\"  ← garbled overflow\nLine 2:  \"nto a loured work counter, t es and shape into ball a a\"                   ← garbled overflow\nLine 3:  \"3 pan over a medium beat y i both sides...\"                                ← garbled overflow\nLine 4:  \"DAT FLATBREADS\"                                                            ← OCR artifact\nLine 5:  \"le Finnish region of Savo 1a bread, it's more like a...\"                   ← body of previous recipe\n...\nLine 16: \"FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS\"                                                   ← correct title #1\n...\nLine 29: \"FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS\"                                                 ← correct title #2\n```\n\nLines 1–3 are clearly garbled sentence fragments (lowercase start, cut-off words). Line 4\nis the tail-end of the previous recipe's title, corrupted by OCR. Lines 5+ are the body\nof that previous recipe. The actual recipes in this file start at line 16.\n\n`findBurstEnd` skips lines 1–3 (garbled, short) but stops at line 4 because `DAT\nFLATBREADS` is ALL_CAPS and not garbled. The prose-preamble check (3+ consecutive body\ntext lines) doesn't fire because line 4 breaks the sequence.\n\n### Proposed fix: Vocabulary corroboration for multi-title candidates\n\nAdd a **corroboration score** to each ALL_CAPS candidate when the multi-title path\n(≥2 ALL_CAPS survivors) is active. The score measures how many of the candidate's\ncontent words appear elsewhere in the document body.\n\n#### Algorithm\n\n```\nfunction corroborationScore(candidate, allLines):\n  contentWords = candidate.text\n    .split(/\\s+/)\n    .filter(w => w.length >= 4)       // skip \"THE\", \"WITH\", \"AND\", etc.\n    .map(w => w.toUpperCase())\n\n  if contentWords.length === 0:\n    return 1.0                          // single short word — can't check, pass through\n\n  corroboratedCount = 0\n  for word in contentWords:\n    // Check if word appears in any other line (not the candidate's own line)\n    for line in allLines:\n      if line.position === candidate.position: continue\n      if line.text.toUpperCase().includes(word):\n        corroboratedCount++\n        break\n\n  return corroboratedCount / contentWords.length\n```\n\n**Integration point:** In the multi-title assembly block (around line 1254), after\nidentifying ≥2 ALL_CAPS survivors but before the sub-header check, filter out candidates\nwith corroboration score below a threshold (e.g., 0.5 — meaning fewer than half of the\ncandidate's content words appear elsewhere in the document).\n\n#### Why this works for the failure case\n\n| Candidate | Content words | Corroborated? | Score |\n|-----------|--------------|---------------|-------|\n| `DAT FLATBREADS` | DAT, FLATBREADS | DAT: **NO** (appears nowhere else), FLATBREADS: YES (lines 16, 29, etc.) | 0.5 |\n| `FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS` | FINNISH, MILK, FLATBREADS | FINNISH: YES (lines 29, 5, etc.), MILK: YES (line 21), FLATBREADS: YES | 1.0 |\n| `FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS` | FINNISH, POTATO, FLATBREADS | FINNISH: YES, POTATO: YES (line 31, 37), FLATBREADS: YES | 1.0 |\n\nWith a threshold of 0.5 (strict >, not ≥), `DAT FLATBREADS` at exactly 0.5 would be\nremoved. With a threshold of `< 0.5` (keep if ≥ 0.5), it would survive.\n\nA safer threshold: require that **all content words of length ≥ 4** are corroborated\n(score = 1.0), OR that the candidate has at least 3 content words with ≥ 2/3 corroborated.\nFor 2-word candidates like `DAT FLATBREADS`, this means both words must appear elsewhere.\n\n**Recommended rule:** For candidates with ≤ 3 content words, require 100% corroboration.\nFor candidates with > 3 content words, require ≥ 67% corroboration. This is strict for\nshort candidates (where a single uncorroborated word is suspicious) and relaxed for long\nones (where one unusual word in a longer title is acceptable).\n\n```typescript\nconst threshold = contentWords.length <= 3 ? 1.0 : 0.67;\nif (corroborationScore < threshold) {\n  // Remove candidate from multi-title assembly\n}\n```\n\nFor `DAT FLATBREADS`: 2 content words, threshold = 1.0, score = 0.5 → **removed**.\n\n#### Why this is safe for other cases\n\n- **Single-title pages** (most recipes): Corroboration is only checked in the multi-title\n  path (≥2 ALL_CAPS survivors). Single-title pages are unaffected.\n\n- **Legitimate compound titles** (e.g., `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE`):\n  These are single candidates with compound separators, not multi-title assembly. Unaffected.\n\n- **Multi-recipe pages** where both titles are real: Both titles' content words will appear\n  in their respective recipe bodies (ingredients, descriptions). They corroborate easily.\n\n- **Very short titles** (1 content word, e.g., a hypothetical `GOLONKA`): The\n  `contentWords.length === 0` guard returns 1.0 for candidates with no words ≥ 4 letters.\n  A single 4+ letter word would need corroboration, which is correct — if the word\n  doesn't appear anywhere in the document, it's suspicious.\n\n### Secondary fix: Improve preamble detection for garbled-then-clean sequences\n\nThe `findBurstEnd` function currently stops at the first non-garbled line. But when\nlines 1–3 are garbled fragments and line 4 is a short ALL_CAPS string, line 4 is very\nlikely part of the same overflow block.\n\n**Proposed heuristic:** After `findBurstEnd` skips garbled lines, if the next line is\nALL_CAPS and ≤ 3 words, AND the line after that starts with lowercase (body text), treat\nthe ALL_CAPS line as the tail of the preamble and skip it too.\n\n```typescript\n// In findBurstEnd, after the garbled-skip loop:\nif (i > 0 && i < lines.length) {\n  const next = lines[i].text;\n  // If burst ended at a short ALL_CAPS fragment followed by body text,\n  // it's likely the truncated title of the previous page's recipe.\n  if (isAllCaps(next) && wordCount(next) <= 3 && i + 1 < lines.length) {\n    const afterNext = lines[i + 1].text;\n    if (/^[a-ząćęłńóśźż]/.test(afterNext) && wordCount(afterNext) >= 4) {\n      i++;  // Skip the ALL_CAPS fragment too\n      // Also skip the body text that follows (same prose-preamble logic)\n      // ...\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nThis is a **complementary** fix. It prevents `DAT FLATBREADS` from entering the candidate\npool at all, which is cleaner than relying solely on corroboration to remove it later.\nHowever, corroboration is the more general defense (handles cases where the preamble\ndetection doesn't fire).\n\n**Risk:** Could skip a legitimate short ALL_CAPS title at the start of a file if preceded\nby garbled text. Mitigation: Only fires when `i > 0` (garbled lines were actually\nskipped) AND the next line is body text (lowercase start, ≥ 4 words). A real title would\ntypically be followed by a subtitle or description, not body text.\n\n### Implementation changes\n\n#### File: `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`\n\n| Change | Location | Description |\n|--------|----------|-------------|\n| Add `corroborationScore()` function | New function, near scoring helpers | Compute vocabulary overlap between candidate and rest of document |\n| Apply corroboration filter in multi-title path | ~line 1254, inside `allCapsSelected.length >= 2` branch | Remove ALL_CAPS candidates below corroboration threshold before sub-header check |\n| Improve `findBurstEnd` for garbled-then-clean sequences | ~line 378, after garbled-skip loop | Skip short ALL_CAPS fragment after garbled burst when followed by body text |\n\nNo new files. No changes to `food-dictionary.ts`, `embeddings.ts`, or test files.\n\n---\n\n## Testing Strategy\n\n### Verifying the fix\n\n1. **Primary:** Run the title-loop evaluation harness (`tools/title-loop/title-loop.py`)\n   and confirm:\n   - `FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS` now passes\n   - No regressions in real or generated files\n\n2. **Unit test cases to add** (in `lib/text-classifier/__tests__/title-extractor.test.ts`):\n\n   - **Corroboration rejects orphaned artifact:** Input with garbled preamble + orphaned\n     ALL_CAPS + 2 real recipe titles → only real titles returned\n   - **Corroboration keeps legitimate multi-recipe:** Input with 2 ALL_CAPS titles that\n     both have body text referencing their words → both kept\n\n3. **Edge case tests:**\n   - Short ALL_CAPS title (2 words) where one word is common (\"CHICKEN SOUP\") and appears\n     in body → kept (both words corroborated)\n   - ALL_CAPS title with an unusual/unique word that doesn't appear in body but is\n     clearly the title → still works because it's the only candidate (single-title path,\n     corroboration not applied)\n\n### What not to test\n\n- Generated file generation — 0 failures, don't add new synthetic cases for this pattern\n- Embedding model behavior — not changed\n- OCR repair — not changed\n\n---\n\n## Performance Considerations\n\nThe corroboration check iterates over candidate content words × document lines. With\ntypical values (2–4 content words, 30–50 lines), this is ~100–200 string operations.\nNegligible compared to the embedding computation (which dominates the 10-second budget).\n\nThe `findBurstEnd` improvement adds a constant-time check. No performance impact.\n\n---\n\n## Security Considerations\n\nNone. All changes are in local text processing with no I/O or user-facing API changes.\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Phases\n\n### Phase 1: Core fix (single change set)\n\n1. Add `corroborationScore()` helper function\n2. Integrate corroboration filter into multi-title assembly (≥2 ALL_CAPS branch)\n3. Improve `findBurstEnd` for garbled-then-clean sequences\n4. Run evaluation harness, confirm fix + no regressions\n\nThis is a single-phase change. The fix is small and targeted.\n\n---\n\n## Open Questions\n\n1. **Corroboration threshold for 2-word candidates:** Should we require 100% (both words\n   corroborated) or allow 50% (at least one word)? The 100% rule is safer for the known\n   failure case but could be too strict for hypothetical titles with one unusual word.\n   **Recommendation:** Start with 100% for ≤ 3 content words. If a regression appears,\n   relax to 50%.\n\n2. **Should corroboration apply to single-title path too?** Currently proposed only for\n   multi-title (≥2 ALL_CAPS). Applying it to single-title would add a safety net but\n   risks rejecting legitimate titles with unique words. **Recommendation:** No — the\n   single-title fallback hierarchy already handles this well enough.\n\n3. **Should `findBurstEnd` improvement be included?** It's a belt-and-suspenders approach.\n   The corroboration check alone would fix the failure. The preamble detection improvement\n   prevents the artifact from entering the candidate pool at all, which is cleaner.\n   **Recommendation:** Include both. They address different layers of the pipeline and\n   neither is risky on its own.\n\n---\n\n## References\n\n- Iteration 25 feedback: `tools/title-loop/docs/25-2331e30/feedback.md`\n- Iteration 24 improvement plan: `tools/title-loop/docs/24-b15aa30/improvement-plan.md`\n- Failing test input: `tools/title-loop/input/FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS.real.txt`\n- Multi-title assembly logic: `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1245-1314`\n- `findBurstEnd`: `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:355-410`\n","numLines":332,"startLine":1,"totalLines":332}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01CPF9PYEtLBXdUb9Q1qDz9j","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 25 Feedback\n     2→\n     3→## Failure count: 1 real, 0 generated\n     4→\n     5→---\n     6→\n     7→## Pattern: OCR artifact mistaken for a title component\n     8→\n     9→**Affects:** Real files only\n    10→\n    11→### What happened\n    12→\n    13→- **Expected:** `FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS`\n    14→- **Extracted:** `DAT FLATBREADS + FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS`\n    15→\n    16→The extractor correctly identified that the document contains two joined recipe titles (compound `+` title). However, it picked the wrong two candidates.\n    17→\n    18→### Root cause\n    19→\n    20→The input contains a visually prominent all-caps string `DAT FLATBREADS` early in the text (line 4). This is an OCR corruption artifact — likely the tail end of a partially-captured or misread title from a preceding page or section. Because it is all-caps and structurally title-like, the extractor treated it as a valid title candidate.\n    21→\n    22→Meanwhile, the second correct title `FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS` either appears later in the document (outside the lines shown) or was heavily corrupted by OCR and became unrecognizable. The extractor substituted the nearby OCR artifact `DAT FLATBREADS` in its place.\n    23→\n    24→`FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS` was correctly extracted as one component, confirming the extractor found it in the body of the text.\n    25→\n    26→### Why this is hard\n    27→\n    28→OCR artifacts that happen to be all-caps and short (2–3 words) are indistinguishable from real titles by surface-level heuristics. The string `DAT FLATBREADS` looks like a plausible recipe title fragment.\n    29→\n    30→### Mitigation directions\n    31→\n    32→- Prefer title candidates that share vocabulary with other text in the document (e.g., `FINNISH`, `POTATO`) over orphaned all-caps strings with no surrounding context.\n    33→- When assembling a compound `+` title, require both components to have corroborating evidence in the document (e.g., a description or ingredient list referencing the same subject).\n    34→- Penalise candidates that appear abruptly at the very start of the recognised text with no leading context — these are more likely to be carry-over artifacts from a previous page.\n    35→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a061f1f0-ad7a-459c-9eae-0adb758ccdd2","uuid":"3b3c5606-c797-4160-9374-a951cfbed4d2","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/25-2331e30/feedback.md","content":"# Iteration 25 Feedback\n\n## Failure count: 1 real, 0 generated\n\n---\n\n## Pattern: OCR artifact mistaken for a title component\n\n**Affects:** Real files only\n\n### What happened\n\n- **Expected:** `FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS`\n- **Extracted:** `DAT FLATBREADS + FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS`\n\nThe extractor correctly identified that the document contains two joined recipe titles (compound `+` title). However, it picked the wrong two candidates.\n\n### Root cause\n\nThe input contains a visually prominent all-caps string `DAT FLATBREADS` early in the text (line 4). This is an OCR corruption artifact — likely the tail end of a partially-captured or misread title from a preceding page or section. Because it is all-caps and structurally title-like, the extractor treated it as a valid title candidate.\n\nMeanwhile, the second correct title `FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS` either appears later in the document (outside the lines shown) or was heavily corrupted by OCR and became unrecognizable. The extractor substituted the nearby OCR artifact `DAT FLATBREADS` in its place.\n\n`FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS` was correctly extracted as one component, confirming the extractor found it in the body of the text.\n\n### Why this is hard\n\nOCR artifacts that happen to be all-caps and short (2–3 words) are indistinguishable from real titles by surface-level heuristics. The string `DAT FLATBREADS` looks like a plausible recipe title fragment.\n\n### Mitigation directions\n\n- Prefer title candidates that share vocabulary with other text in the document (e.g., `FINNISH`, `POTATO`) over orphaned all-caps strings with no surrounding context.\n- When assembling a compound `+` title, require both components to have corroborating evidence in the document (e.g., a description or ingredient list referencing the same subject).\n- Penalise candidates that appear abruptly at the very start of the recognised text with no leading context — these are more likely to be carry-over artifacts from a previous page.\n","numLines":35,"startLine":1,"totalLines":35}}}
